metadata.name: The Likeness of a Flower #17
metadata.description:
And the unseen eyebeam crossed, for the roses
Had the look of flowers that are looked at.
- T.S. Eliot, Four Quartets: Burnt Norton (1936)

This work is an attempt to encapsulate in an algorithm, not the likeness of a flower, but the likeness of a painting of a flower. If, according to a very old definition, art is an imitation of nature, this is an imitation of an imitation – a sort of meta-imitation of nature by means of computer code.

The challenge for this piece was to capture some of the looseness and fluidity of the human hand when holding a brush or a pencil, and reproducing some typical forms of hand-made scribbles, doodles and brush strokes. However, absent the materiality of paint and canvas, everything is simulated here on the base of a very simple resource: circles. Everything you see is built of very many overlapping circles of varying sizes, colors and opacities. It is circles all the way down…

Inspiration for this work comes from a number of expressionist painters, from 20th century classics like Cy Twombly, to the magnificent contemporary work of Philip Maltman: https://www.instagram.com/philipmaltman/

This work is animated.
Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 1000 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be slow.

Made with the open-source libraries p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Haemo Globs #208
metadata.description:
The shape and function of haematids (red blood cells) has always fascinated me. Perhaps their mathematical smoothness and candy-like aspect resonated with me as a child. Their simple appearance distinguished them from the other cell types I had learned about. I imagined them engorged with sweet-flavoured oxygen and juicily popping under my bite.

I hope for this generative artwork to communicate my appreciation for these never-ending body travellers.

metadata.name: We Are Alone Together #377
metadata.description:
We meander through the flows of life, alone but together. This experience — an ultimately solitary one — is communicated but never truly shared. Our consciousnesses live in a perpetual separated state, alone but together.

############

Display resolution scales with window size. Press ’h’ (in live mode) to generate a 6000x7500 hi-res image. This may take a few seconds to generate depending on your hardware. Press ‘d’ to redraw the artwork.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #85
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an “artificial nature” which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that’s always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture

metadata.name: I AM UNFOLDING #30
metadata.description:
In the past, I was but fragments
Rough and jagged
Indefinitely, I weathered and grew
A sculpture formed, unstructured

In the present, I am the precipice
A grandiose monolith
My angles sharp, my lines precise
A work of art, restructured

The future looms before
A blank formlessness yet to be
My function undefined
In perpetuity, unfolding

-----------------------------------------

Best efforts have been made to optimize this project; however, for best performance, a machine with a dedicated GPU is recommended. Viewing the project in live mode is also recommended.

S - export a high resolution image.
P - pause the animation.

metadata.name: Komposite #2
metadata.description:
Celebrating Genuary 2023, Komposite is a collection exploring minimalism and bringing together few smaller building blocks to build up a more complex and interesting composite effect. The project is an exploration of patterns, shapes, and composition, hoping to build up on these in the future. Happy Genuary :)

Press 's' in live mode to save the output in png format.

Press '2', '3' in live mode to save higher resolution output in png format (may take a moment).

metadata.name: Learning to Draw #45
metadata.description:
It's a collaboration between the computer and me. I tried to teach them to draw like a human artist, with all the imperfection that it means, and they tried to teach me to draw as a computer artist, with all the perfection that it means. The result is a cluster of approximative dots, jiggly lines and perfect bubbles, highlighted by colors carefully selected by them and me, after a long night of review, arguing and drinking red wine.

This is both of us, learning to draw.

PS: If any wanted or unwanted bug is found in an iteration, consider it as a blessing from the Genart Gods

Cheat codes:
* Press 1-8 to change resolution (or add &res=x to the url)
* Press s to save a PNG (or add &s=1 to the url)
